// Sutra corpus test: ordered comparison — number-axis only.
//
// `>`, `<`, `>=`, `<=` are ordering relations on real values, not
// fuzzy-logic operators. They work on number-family operands
// (int, float, complex's real axis, char, scalar) and produce a
// truth-axis vector. The mechanism:
//
//   1. Matrix-multiply both sides by a real-axis projector —
//      zeros every axis except synthetic[AXIS_REAL].
//   2. Read the real scalars; compute diff = a_real - b_real.
//   3. Output make_truth(sign(diff)):
//        diff > 0  → +1 (true)
//        diff < 0  → -1 (false)
//        diff == 0 → 0  (unknown — a value can't strictly exceed itself)
//
// `>=` and `<=` produce the same polynomial as `>` and `<`, because
// ties give 0 either way (unknown). On integers this is the sign
// function; it's not smooth at 0, but integers don't hover there
// under gradient flow, so this is fine.
//
// Comparing truth-family values (bool / fuzzy / trit) with `>` is
// a compile-time error — ordering isn't a natural operation on a
// truth axis. Classes can override `<` / `>` if they want custom
// comparison semantics for their own types.

function fuzzy IntGt() {
    int a = 5;
    int b = 3;
    return a > b;                 // +1 (true)
}

function fuzzy IntLt() {
    int a = 3;
    int b = 5;
    return a > b;                 // -1 (false)
}

function fuzzy IntEqual() {
    int a = 7;
    int b = 7;
    return a > b;                 // 0 (unknown — tie)
}

function fuzzy FloatCmp() {
    float a = 3.14;
    float b = 2.71;
    return a > b;                 // +1
}

function fuzzy NegativeCmp() {
    int a = -5;
    int b = -3;
    return a > b;                 // -1 (-5 is less than -3)
}

// `<` is the mirror of `>`.
function fuzzy LessThan() {
    int a = 3;
    int b = 5;
    return a < b;                 // +1 (true)
}
